            <fr:number>5.2.4</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We will need to make precise the above construction when passing to derived categories, and to give a relative variant of it.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the constant simplicial space defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> with augmentation map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon \colon  S_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_\bullet \colon  X_\bullet \to  S_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the map induced by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex>.
    Then

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2358</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.4.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         a_*         = \varepsilon _* {a_\bullet }_*\colon          (X_\bullet )^\sim          \to  (S)^\sim .       \tag{5.2.4.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>The derived version of this equation is

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2359</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.4.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.4.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R} a_*         = \mathrm {R}\varepsilon _* \mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*\colon          \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )         \to  \mathrm {D}^+(S)         \to  (S)^\sim .       \tag{5.2.4.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> is the bounded-below derived category of the category of abelian sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We will calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}{a_\bullet }_*]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\varepsilon _*]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
